Narrative:
Round-1 audit of timeout increase from 600s to 3600s. Found 2 CRITICAL consistency issues: (1) fallback in poller.py line 65 still hardcoded to 600s instead of new 3600s default, creating silent timeout mismatch for template-less polling scenarios; (2) wait_for_status() default parameter not synchronized—still 600s, though currently masked by explicit callers. Also identified maintainability risks: implicit default removal (from inline task creation) reduces auditability, no per-task timeout configurability added for CLI, and zero test coverage for timeout paths. Resource impact acceptable (per-iteration basis), but lack of metrics justifying 6x increase is concerning.

Findings:
- [Critical] factory/poller.py:65 Update poller.py line 65 fallback from 600 to 3600 to match new CoderConfig default. This ensures consistency across all code paths that instantiate CoderConfig.
  description: The poller.py issue_to_task() function creates a CoderConfig with a hardcoded fallback of 600s when template.coder is None. This fallback was not updated when CoderConfig.session_timeout default was increased to 3600s in models.py. This creates a silent inconsistency: polling without an explicit coder template will use 600s instead of the new 3600s default, potentially causing premature timeouts in edge cases where templates lack coder config.
- [Critical] factory/session.py:191 Synchronize wait_for_status() default parameter with CoderConfig default. Either: (1) update default to 3600, or (2) remove the default entirely and require explicit timeout at all call sites. Option 2 is safer for preventing silent timeout mismatches.
  description: The wait_for_status() function defines its own default parameter timeout=600 (line 191). While all current callers in runner.py explicitly pass timeout=task.coder.session_timeout (correctly using 3600s), this orphaned default creates a maintenance hazard. If future code calls wait_for_status() without an explicit timeout argument, it will silently revert to 600s instead of 3600s. This violates the single-source-of-truth principle and makes the codebase fragile to refactoring.
- [Warning] factory/cli.py:133 Consider adding a `--session-timeout` CLI option to _build_inline_task() for per-task configurability. Document the default timeout behavior clearly in the function docstring and in CLI help text.
  description: The commit removed `session_timeout=600` from _build_inline_task(), replacing it with reliance on the model's default (now 3600s). While this reduces duplication, it makes the timeout value implicit in the code. Code reviewers and maintainers must now consult factory/models.py to understand what timeout an inline task gets. The old explicit value was more discoverable during code review. Additionally, there is no CLI flag (e.g., `--session-timeout`) to override the timeout for individual inline tasks.
- [Warning] factory/runner.py:210-212 Verify that actual coder execution times for target workloads fit comfortably within 3600s per iteration. Provide baseline metrics or profiling data to justify the 6x timeout increase. Document the maximum total execution time (including eval/crucible/evaluator phases) in task configuration.
  description: Each coder iteration gets the full session_timeout (now 3600s). With max_iterations=3 (default), that's 3 × 3600s = 10,800s for coder alone. Additionally, each iteration runs eval (300s), crucible (600s), and evaluator (120s) if enabled. Total per-iteration: 3600 + 300 + 600 + 120 = 4620s (77 minutes). The commit message and focus areas do not address whether these compounding timeouts have been validated against actual workload requirements.
- [Warning] <unknown> Add unit tests for: (1) wait_for_status() behavior with both explicit and default timeouts, (2) issue_to_task() timeout handling with/without template coder, (3) timeout logging and RunState transition when timeout occurs, (4) resource cleanup after timeout (session kill, port release).
  description: Per CLAUDE.md, 'No tests exist yet — the main way to verify changes is running a task end-to-end.' This timeout change affects critical control flow (timeout detection at line 290-298 in runner.py) but has no unit or integration tests. Edge cases like: wait_for_status() called without explicit timeout, poller creating tasks without coder template, concurrent 3600s sessions on worker, timeout message logging — none are tested. Risk of silent failures in edge paths.
- [Info] factory/runner.py:290-298 Verify the logic in wait_for_status(): the loop condition `while elapsed < timeout:` and the increment `elapsed += poll_interval` ensure that the function returns 'timeout' within ±poll_interval (5s) of the target timeout. With 3600s timeout and 5s poll interval, this is acceptable precision.
  description: The timeout detection at line 290 correctly checks if wait_for_status() returns 'timeout' and logs the session_timeout value in run.notes. However, this assumes wait_for_status() will always return 'timeout' when elapsed >= timeout. Verify that the polling loop in session.py line 202-224 correctly enforces the timeout boundary and does not continue looping beyond the specified timeout.
- [Info] factory/session.py:217-220 Consider adding log entries to understand resource utilization during long-running iterations. Example: memory usage, CPU %, number of active tmux panes.
  description: The wait_for_status() function logs 'still running...' heartbeat every 60 seconds (line 217-220). With the new 3600s timeout, engineers will see ~60 status updates per iteration, providing good visibility into long-running tasks. This is a positive aspect of the change.
- [Info] factory/models.py:41-55 Add detailed comment explaining the timeout rationale: typical execution times, what workloads require >600s, what symptoms led to the timeout increase, and any trade-offs (e.g., resource cost of longer-lived sessions).
  description: The CoderConfig class comment for session_timeout (line 44) reads only '# seconds to wait for the agent to finish per iteration' with no context about why 3600s was chosen or what workloads require this duration. The change from 600s to 3600s is a 6x increase, but no metrics, profiling, or user feedback is documented to justify the threshold.

