  "analysis_markdown": "## Local Diff Analysis\n\nIncreased CoderConfig session_timeout default from 600s (10 min) to 3600s (1 hour) to fix premature task timeouts. The default is now defined once in the Pydantic model, and the explicit override in inline task creation was removed to use the new default. This addresses timeout failures during agent execution iterations where 10 minutes proved insufficient.\n\n### Suggested Review Focus\n- Timeout adequacy validation: 10x increase is significant; reviewers must confirm 1 hour is sufficient for target workloads without being excessive. No baseline metrics provided for typical coder execution times.\n- Stuck task detection: Longer timeout increases risk of masking genuinely hung agents. Verify monitoring/logging exists to distinguish legitimate slow execution from infinite loops or deadlocks.\n- Resource contention on worker: Longer-held tmux sessions and SSH connections multiply resource pressure. Check if worker has capacity and cleanup guarantees for 60+ concurrent 1-hour sessions.\n- Timeout application scope: Verify this timeout applies uniformly across all coder→eval retry cycles (max_iterations=3). Each iteration gets full 3600s?\n- User experience impact: Failures now take up to 1 hour to surface. Confirm feedback loops and retry logic handle this latency appropriately.\n\n### Trade-offs\n- Prevents premature timeout failures but increases latency for blocked/hung tasks — relies on external monitoring to catch legitimately stuck agents\n- Worker resources (tmux sessions, disk, memory) held 6x longer per iteration — requires validation that worker capacity and cleanup mechanisms handle sustained load\n- Removed explicit timeout override in inline task creation makes behavior implicit and harder to audit — now depends on class default which could drift in future refactors\n- No per-task timeout configurability — all tasks get 1 hour regardless of complexity; may be over-provisioned for simple tasks\n\n### Affected Modules\n- factory/models.py — CoderConfig class, session_timeout field default\n- factory/cli.py — _build_inline_task() function, CoderConfig instantiation\n- factory/runner.py — run_task() likely uses CoderConfig.session_timeout in polling loop\n- factory/session.py — RemoteSession likely uses timeout when polling .factory/status file\n\n### Call Chain\n- cli.py:_build_inline_task() → creates TaskDefinition with CoderConfig(session_timeout=3600 via default)\n- runner.py:run_task(task) → extracts task.coder.session_timeout\n- session.py:RemoteSession.poll() → waits up to 3600s for .factory/status == 'done'\n- evaluator.py:run_eval() → executes post-coder validation, may also respect timeout\n\n### Design Patterns\n- Pydantic config object with typed defaults — centralizes timeout configuration\n- Default-over-explicit pattern — removed hardcoded value to rely on class default, reduces duplication but increases implicit behavior\n- Config inheritance — CoderConfig timeout applies uniformly to all execution paths that use it\n\n### Reviewer Checklist\n- Search codebase for other hardcoded `session_timeout` values (600, 3600, etc.) to ensure no orphaned configs\n- Verify session.py and runner.py correctly propagate CoderConfig.session_timeout to the polling loop\n- Check logs/metrics for typical coder execution times — confirm 3600s is data-driven, not a guess\n- Inspect worker cleanup: do timed-out or completed sessions properly release tmux/SSH resources within minutes?\n- Confirm evaluator.py timeout behavior: does it inherit from CoderConfig or have its own timeout?\n- Review Slack notifications / alerts: do they fire before timeout occurs, or only after?\n- Test scenario: intentionally slow coder task — verify it completes within 3600s and doesn't hang beyond\n- Consider if timeout should be task-parameter or per-agent (e.g., 'claude' may need more time than 'codex')\n",
