  "pr_comment_markdown": "## Crucible Review Summary\n\n- Issues: 15\n- Critical: 4, Warning: 7\n\n### Top Actions\n- [Critical] Timeout parameter inconsistency across multiple code paths (<unknown>)\n- [Critical] Incomplete implementation: poller.py and session.py not updated in round-2 fix (<unknown>)\n- [Critical] Hardcoded timeout fallback not synchronized with CoderConfig default change (factory/poller.py:65)\n- [Critical] wait_for_status() default timeout parameter not synchronized with CoderConfig (factory/session.py:191)\n- [Warning] Incomplete round-2 fix misses critical Round-1 findings (<unknown>)\n- [Warning] No test coverage for timeout behavior; change relies entirely on manual end-to-end testing (<unknown>)\n- [Warning] No unit tests added for timeout behavior (Round 1 requirement) (<unknown>)\n- [Warning] No unit tests added for timeout behavior across all code paths (<unknown>)\n- [Warning] Removed explicit timeout parameter makes inline task timeout behavior implicit and hard to audit (factory/cli.py:133)\n- [Warning] Per-iteration timeout multiplier not documented; total runtime could exceed 4600s with all phases enabled (factory/runner.py:210)\n- [Warning] Per-iteration timeout multiplier effect not documented; total runtime could exceed 4600s per iteration with all phases enabled (factory/runner.py:210)\n\n### Notable Issues\n- **Timeout parameter inconsistency across multiple code paths** `<unknown>`: Three separate locations maintain timeout defaults that are not synchronized: (1) poller.py:65 has hardcoded fallback of 600s when template.coder is None, (2) session.py:191 defines wait_for_status() default parameter as 600s, and (3) cli.py:133 previously had explicit 600s but was removed. While current call sites in runner.py pass explicit timeout=task.coder.session_timeout (3600s), these orphaned defaults create maintenance hazards. Future code paths that instantiate CoderConfig or call wait_for_status() without explicit timeout arguments will silently revert to 600s instead of the intended 3600s, causing premature timeouts.\n- **Incomplete implementation: poller.py and session.py not updated in round-2 fix** `<unknown>`: Round 1 review identified four critical/warning findings requiring synchronization of timeout parameters across CoderConfig, wait_for_status(), poller fallback, and CLI. The round-2 commit only partially addressed these issues: factory/models.py:41 (CoderConfig default increased to 3600) and factory/cli.py:133 (removed hardcoded 600) were fixed, but factory/poller.py:65 and factory/session.py:191 remain unaddressed with their original 600s defaults. This leaves the fix incomplete and undermines the stated goal of 'consistency across all code paths.' Reviewers should not approve this commit until all four locations are synchronized.\n- **Hardcoded timeout fallback not synchronized with CoderConfig default change** `factory/poller.py:65`: The poller.py issue_to_task() function creates a CoderConfig with a hardcoded fallback of 600s when template.coder is None. This fallback was not updated when CoderConfig.session_timeout default was increased to 3600s in models.py. This creates a silent inconsistency: polling without an explicit coder template will use 600s instead of the new 3600s default, potentially causing premature timeouts in edge cases where templates lack coder config.\n- **wait_for_status() default timeout parameter not synchronized with CoderConfig** `factory/session.py:191`: The wait_for_status() function defines its own default parameter timeout=600 (line 191). While all current callers in runner.py explicitly pass timeout=task.coder.session_timeout (correctly using 3600s), this orphaned default creates a maintenance hazard. If future code calls wait_for_status() without an explicit timeout argument, it will silently revert to 600s instead of 3600s. This violates the single-source-of-truth principle and makes the codebase fragile to refactoring.\n- **Incomplete round-2 fix misses critical Round-1 findings** `<unknown>`: The diff addresses only 2 of the 4 critical/warning locations identified in Round 1 review. Specifically: (1) cli.py:133 fix is implemented (removed hardcoded 600), (2) models.py:41 default is increased to 3600, BUT (3) poller.py:65 is NOT fixed, and (4) session.py:191 is NOT fixed. This suggests either incomplete implementation or misunderstanding of scope. The Round 1 review explicitly required both poller.py and session.py to be updated for 'consistency across all code paths.'\n- **No test coverage for timeout behavior; change relies entirely on manual end-to-end testing** `<unknown>`: Per CLAUDE.md, 'No tests exist yet — the main way to verify changes is running a task end-to-end.' This timeout change affects critical control flow (timeout detection at line 290-298 in runner.py) but has no unit or integration tests. Edge cases like: wait_for_status() called without explicit timeout, poller creating tasks without coder template, concurrent 3600s sessions on worker, timeout message logging — none are tested. Risk of silent failures in edge paths.\n- **No unit tests added for timeout behavior (Round 1 requirement)** `<unknown>`: Round 1 flagged: 'factory/cli.py:133 Consider adding... Document the default timeout behavior clearly in the function docstring and in CLI help text' and 'Add unit tests for: (1) wait_for_status() behavior with both explicit and default timeouts, (2) issue_to_task() timeout handling with/without template coder, (3) timeout logging and RunState transition when timeout occurs, (4) resource cleanup after timeout (session kill, port release).' The diff includes zero new tests. This is concerning because: (1) timeout logic is mission-critical — incorrect timeouts cause task failures, (2) three separate timeout paths exist (CoderConfig default, wait_for_status default, poller.py fallback), (3) without tests, future refactors risk re-introducing timeout mismatches.\n- **No unit tests added for timeout behavior across all code paths** `<unknown>`: The timeout change affects mission-critical control flow (timeout detection, RunState transitions, session cleanup) but adds zero test coverage. Three separate timeout defaults exist (CoderConfig, wait_for_status(), poller.py fallback), creating three separate edge cases. Per CLAUDE.md, 'No tests exist yet — the main way to verify changes is running a task end-to-end,' which is insufficient for a 6x timeout multiplier change. Untested edge cases include: (1) wait_for_status() called without explicit timeout (uses default), (2) poller creating tasks without coder template (uses fallback), (3) concurrent 3600s sessions on worker (resource impact), (4) timeout message logging and RunState.failed transition, (5) tmux session cleanup and port release after timeout.\n- **Removed explicit timeout parameter makes inline task timeout behavior implicit and hard to audit** `factory/cli.py:133`: The commit removed `session_timeout=600` from _build_inline_task(), replacing it with reliance on the model's default (now 3600s). While this reduces duplication, it makes the timeout value implicit in the code. Code reviewers and maintainers must now consult factory/models.py to understand what timeout an inline task gets. The old explicit value was more discoverable during code review. Additionally, there is no CLI flag (e.g., `--session-timeout`) to override the timeout for individual inline tasks.\n- **Per-iteration timeout multiplier not documented; total runtime could exceed 4600s with all phases enabled** `factory/runner.py:210`: Each coder iteration gets the full session_timeout (now 3600s). With max_iterations=3 (default), that's 3 × 3600s = 10,800s for coder alone. Additionally, each iteration runs eval (300s), crucible (600s), and evaluator (120s) if enabled. Total per-iteration: 3600 + 300 + 600 + 120 = 4620s (77 minutes). The commit message and focus areas do not address whether these compounding timeouts have been validated against actual workload requirements.\n",
